As the uncertain components of the HF, three cases with different HF density were calculated and compared (Table 2
). For case C, the molecular weight of the fog-haze is assumed to be 44, which is about 150% the molecular weight of air. For case D, the fog-haze has the same density of air. For case E, the fog-haze is 50% lighter than air. Initially, 10% of HF fully occupied the lower half of the tunnel, as depicted in Fig. 7
(a). It should be mentioned that in this simulation no additional pollutant resources were included. The uniformly distributed HF will be discharged out of the tunnel by wind. This guarantees that the computed results are free of the position effect of air pollutant sources.
